">           Before we delve into whether or not committing genocide on harmful intelligences is ever morally justified, we must first decide what is is that makes an intelligence “harmful”. The first part of this definition is easy; harmful simply refers to something that causes harm. However, the second part proves to be more challenging: what is harm? Moral philosopher Bernard Gert asserts that there are “five harms that all rational persons want to avoid” (1). These five harms are as follows:

                               1. Don’t kill (Don’t cause permanent loss of consciousness.)
                               2. Don’t cause pain. (This includes mental pain as well as physical pain.)
                               3. Don’t disable. (Don’t cause loss of ability.)
                               4. Don’t deprive of freedom (or opportunity).
                               5. Don’t deprive of pleasure. (Gert 10)

           Therefore, a “harmful intelligence” is an intelligent being or species that knowingly causes one of the five harms or does not knowingly cause harm but cannot be changed so that it no longer does. Through this, it is immediately clear why The Terminator should be considered a harmful intelligence. It’s sole reason for existence was to go back in time, find Sarah Connor, and murder her (Cameron, The Terminator). It is more difficult to judge whether or not the noocytes are harmful. However, the noocytes ultimately deprive humanity of freedom. Specifically, they deprive them of the freedom to choose whether they would like to remain as an individual human or join the noosphere. For the most part, the noocytes transform people without their permission, such as between Edward and Gail, when they merged together (Bear, 114). Still, it may be argued that at one point noocytes gave Suzy the choice to “continue like [she was], or to join us” (Bear 219). Ultimately, though, the noocytes changed Suzy, as well as the rest of humanity (Bear 275-276). Another issue that further complicates the issue of “harmfulness” is the fear of the unknown. This would likely cause most people to overestimate just how “harmful” the intelligences are:

           [Video Script, in the style of a news clip]
           Newscaster: We are receiving reports of a previously unknown intelligent species that has been discovered in California. Experts do not know much about this species yet, but it seems as if they are acting in similar ways to a disease. People have reported while lines across their body as well as sudden, overwhelming fatigue. At the moment, it is recommended that you distance yourself from anyone showing these symptoms to prevent the further spread of these cells. (to earpiece) I’m sorry? (to camera) This just in, there are many cases in the California area of missing people who earlier showed symptoms. We have the daughter of one of the missing cases, whose identity has not been released, on the line right now.
           Daughter: It doesn’t make any sense. Just this morning, my mother was right there in bed. Yeah, she seemed sick, but it certainly didn’t seem fatal. Then I came home from school and she was just...gone. Her clothes were still there, but that was it. It doesn’t make any sense. It can’t be real. It can’t be real. It can’t be re---”
           Newscaster: At the moment, we can not confirm that these disappearances are in any way related to the new intelligent species. There is no reason to panic. However, we strongly urge you- please stay away from anyone exhibiting any symptoms.
           [end video]
           	Despite the fact that the noocytes are classified as “harmful”, humanity is not right in attempting to commit acts of genocide. This is because the noocytes are conscious organisms with an intelligence comparable to that of a human (working together, their intelligence is even greater). Since they are conscious and intelligent, the noocytes are aware that others “wish to destroy *the lab*, and presumably all of us” (Bear 226). Throughout the surrounding passages, the noocytes express unease and desperation at the thought of genocide on their own species. Their desperation does not manifest itself in an emotional way, as it would in humans. Instead, the noocytes express desperation through repeated logical questioning, asking “Can you stop these attempts?” (Bear 227). Of course, it would be inaccurate to call noocytes the same as humans, but there are certainly equivalencies: both are conscious, intelligent, and are desperate to maintain survival (not to mention, noocytes are made from human blood cells). The distinction is further blurred by the fact that noocytes live within humans and, in order to advance themselves, merge multiple humans together to create a human-noocyte organism, where each is a part of the other. Since “the principle that any national, racial or religious group has a natural right to exist”, the humans that the noocytes inhabit have the right to exist, as do the humans (Destexhe). In fact, the transformed humans form their own “group”, so any systematic killing of transformed humans would be considered genocide, which is a violation of the human right to exist and therefore immoral. Since the noocytes are an essential part of this new group of humans, these same rights should extend to them as well. So, genocide of noocytes violates their right to exist, which is unethical.</p>
