">The main argument that can be made in favor of committing genocide in dire circumstances is the possibility that genocide of other intelligent species is the only method of ensuring humanity’s survival. However, this is viewpoint is very anthropocentric- the logic only follows if humanity is the most important thing in existence. In other words, say it was considered that it was morally right for humanity to commit genocide on the noocytes to ensure survival. Is it then morally right for the Terminator and similar AIs to commit genocide on all of humanity? If humans are not the most important thing in existence, then there is no difference between these two scenarios. Most people would be very quick to agree that it is immoral for the Terminator to kill Sarah Connor (and thus kill all hope for humanity’s survival in the future). Therefore, it is equally immoral for humans to destroy every single noocyte.
Even if an artificially intelligent specie falls within the guidelines of "harmful" as defined previously, it would still be immoral for humanity to commit genocide on them. In the singularity, AI is considered living and conscious. When we murder something, it is essentially taking away their ability to live and to exist, without their consent. As a result, in her article "If Machines Can Think, Do They Deserve Civil Rights?", futurist scholar and science journalist Raya Bidshahri says that, if we extinguished a self-aware artificial intelligent, we would be infringing on the basic right to live. Additionally, once a machine is self-conscious and can demand or is aware that it would like rights, if humans then decided to reprogram them so that they no longer had consciousness, it would be immoral, since that would essentially be killing and refusing their right to survive and thrive. Bidshari also addresses counterarguments that say that, it would be preposterous to give AI rights since they would always be, at some level, programmed to be good or evil by humans. Yet, there are still debates regarding whether humans truly have free will. Many would agree that, regardless of whether or not it turns out that humans have free will or not, we should still have basic rights, such as living. Thus, it is immoral for humans to commit genocide on self-aware androids, however that does not mean that, if humanity were attacked, such as in The Terminator, they should remain as “sitting ducks,”  allowing other intelligences to destroy them. The humans had the right to rebel and start a war in The Terminator. They were not necessarily seeking to destroy the AI, but they were fighting for survival. Had they not rebelled, humanity surely would have gone extinct. That being said, any fighting should stop if an agreement is made between humans and androids that both parties agree on. Similarly, in Blood Music, the humans were justified in their policy of attempting to quarantine the noocytes in North America. This does not target any specific group simply for existing, nor is it designed to kill all or part of a group. Instead, it is fighting back against a group that has been deemed harmful to humanity and is a type of warfare needed for humanity’s survival. Again, as long as any fighting tops when an agreement is reached, there is moral justification for their actions. If an intelligence is deemed “harmful”, humanity does have the option of fighting back, as long as they do not cross over into genocide.</p>
